Nkandla, President Jacob Zuma s homestead in KwaZulu-Natal, is not heading for an upgrade.This was the reply given by Public Works Minister Nathi Nhleko, in response to a written Parliamentary question from the leader of the DA, Mmusi Maimane.Maimane asked Nhleko if his department intended to repair, upgrade or renovate any buildings on the president s private property at Nkandla. Nhleko replied: The department does not intend to repair, upgrade or renovate anything on the president s private property at Nkandla. Maimane also asked Nhleko how many employees in his department were suspended as a result of their involvement in the upgrades at the president s homestead.The answer to this questions was restricted to one word: None. Meanwhile, in another Parliamentary question, this time from DA member of Parliament Alan McLoughlin, Sports Minister Thulas Nxesi said the expenditure incurred by the South African Sports Federation and Olympic Committee towards hosting the 2022 Commonwealth Games was being verified. He gave this answer in reply to a question of how the R118m that went into the bid had been spent.McLoughlin also inquired what the reason was for the bid failing and why Durban was replaced as host city.Nxesi said: The information asked for by the honourable member shall be provided before long. DENNIS CRUYWAGENdennisc@thenewage.co.za